  "slug": "pelmeni",
  "title": "Pelmeni",
  "subtitle": "Russian meat dumplings",
  "excerpt": "Thin dough rounds filled with seasoned pork and onion, folded and pinched into their characteristic half-moon shape, then boiled and eaten with butter and soured cream or in a bowl of clear broth.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Pelmeni originate in Siberia and the Urals, where they were made in large batches in winter and frozen outdoors for storage. Documented in Lesley Chamberlain, The Food and Cooking of Eastern Europe (1989) and Elena Molokhovets, A Gift to Young Housewives (1861, modern reprint). They are now a staple across Russia.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Making pelmeni is a task for an afternoon and ideally several pairs of hands. In Russia it is traditionally a family activity, everyone gathered around a table, rolling dough, filling, folding, pinching. The process is slow but meditative, and the reward is a large batch that can be frozen and cooked throughout the winter.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The dough must be thin: 2 mm. Any thicker and the dumpling is heavy and stodgy. The filling should be well-seasoned and slightly loose in texture; dense filling makes the pelmeni tough. Fold the filled circle in half, press the edge firmly to seal, then bring the two corners together and press them, this creates the characteristic bonnet shape.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
